        <div class="faq-section">
            <h2>About Stem Cell Transplantation</h2>

            <details>
                <summary>What is stem cell transplantation?</summary>
                <p>Stem cell transplantation is a medical procedure where healthy stem cells are introduced into a
                    patient's body to replace damaged or diseased cells. These cells can develop into different types of
                    blood cells and help rebuild a healthy immune system.</p>
            </details>

            <details>
                <summary>Who is eligible for stem cell transplantation?</summary>
                <p>Eligibility depends on various factors including age, overall health condition, type of disease, and
                    stage of condition. Common conditions treated include leukemia, lymphoma, multiple myeloma, and
                    certain immune system disorders.</p>
            </details>

            <details>
                <summary>What are the different types of stem cell transplants?</summary>
                <p>There are two main types: autologous (using your own stem cells) and allogeneic (using stem cells
                    from a donor). The choice depends on your condition, availability of donors, and other medical
                    factors.</p>
            </details>

            <details>
                <summary>What is the success rate of stem cell transplantation?</summary>
                <p>Success rates vary depending on factors like disease type, stage, age, and overall health. Modern
                    transplants have shown significant improvements in outcomes, with many patients achieving long-term
                    remission.</p>
            </details>

            <details>
                <summary>How long is the recovery period?</summary>
                <p>Recovery typically takes 3-12 months, though this varies by individual. The first 30-100 days are
                    most critical. During this time, patients need close monitoring and follow specific care guidelines
                    to prevent complications.</p>
            </details>
        </div>
